Design Patterns are reusable solutions to common software design problems.
There are 23 design patterns, categorized into 3 types.
Creational patterns (5) deal with object creation (e.g., Singleton, Factory).
Structural patterns (7) focus on class and object relationships (e.g., Adapter, Proxy).
Behavioral patterns (11) define communication between objects (e.g., Observer, Strategy).
These patterns improve code reusability, flexibility, and maintainability.
They are widely used in frameworks like Spring and Hibernate.

1. Creational Design Patterns
   Creational Design Patterns deal with how objects are created in a flexible and reusable way.
   They help avoid tight coupling by hiding the object creation logic from the client.
   Instead of using direct object creation (new), they provide controlled and optimized ways to instantiate objects.
   These patterns improve code maintainability and scalability, especially in large applications.
   Common examples include Singleton, Factory Method, Abstract Factory, Builder, and Prototype.

2. Structural Design Patterns
   Structural Design Patterns deal with how classes and objects are arranged and connected.
   They help in building flexible and efficient relationships between components.
   These patterns make the system easy to extend and maintain.
   They reduce complexity by using wrappers and interfaces.
   Examples include Adapter, Facade, Proxy, Decorator, and Composite.

3. Behavioral Design Patterns
   Behavioral Design Patterns focus on communication between objects.
   They define how objects interact and delegate responsibilities.
   These patterns help make systems flexible and loosely coupled.
   They improve the flow of control and object collaboration.
